    {
      "title": "Leibnitz's Rule for Differentiation under the sign of integration ",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Leibnitz's Rule for differentiation&nbsp;</strong></h3><p><strong>Case-I. </strong>If the limits are function of the variable whose derivative is taken.</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{. }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\frac{d}{dx}\\underset{\\text{independent }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }x}{\\mathop{\\underset{{}}{\\mathop{\\left[ \\mathop{\\int }_{g\\left( x \\right)}^{h\\left( x \\right)}f\\left( t \\right)dt \\right]}}\\,}}\\,=f\\left[ h\\left( x \\right) \\right]\\times {h}'\\left( x \\right)-f\\left[ g\\left( x \\right) \\right]\\times {g}'\\left( x \\right)$</p><p>a very common case is</p><p>$\\frac{d}{dx}\\mathop{\\int }_{0}^{x}f\\left( t \\right)dt=f\\left( x \\right)$</p><p><strong>Case-2. </strong>If the integrand is the function of variable whose derivative is taken, i.e.</p><p>$\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[ \\mathop{\\int }_{a}^{b}f\\left( x,t \\right)dt \\right]=\\mathop{\\int }_{a}^{b}\\frac{d}{dx}f\\left( x,t \\right)dt$</p><p>taking $\\text{t}$ as a constant while differentiating.</p><p><strong>Case-3. </strong>General Case :</p><p>$\\frac{d}{dx}\\mathop{\\int }_{g\\left( x \\right)}^{h\\left( x \\right)}f\\left( t,x \\right)dt=\\mathop{\\int }_{g\\left( x \\right)}^{h\\left( x \\right)}\\frac{d}{dx}f\\left( t,x \\right)dt+f\\left[ h\\left( x \\right) \\right]{h}'\\left( x \\right)-f\\left[ g\\left( x \\right) \\right]\\times {g}'\\left( x \\right)$</p><p>You can see that its a combination of both the results.</p><p><strong>TIP :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Learn the formulas by variable of differentiation, integrand &amp; limit of the integral not by cases.</p><p><strong>Property-18. </strong>Let a function $\\text{f}\\left( \\text{x},\\text{a} \\right)$ be continuous for $\\text{a}\\le \\text{x}\\le \\text{b}$ and $\\text{c}\\le \\alpha \\le \\text{d}$. Then for any $\\alpha \\in \\left[ \\text{c},\\text{d} \\right]$, if $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ I}\\left( \\alpha \\right)=\\int _{\\text{a}}^{\\text{b}}\\text{f}\\left( \\text{x},\\alpha \\right)\\text{dx}$, then</p><p>\\(\\frac{\\mathrm{dI}(\\alpha)}{\\mathrm{d} \\alpha}=\\int_{\\mathrm{a}}^{\\mathrm{b}} \\frac{\\partial(\\mathrm{f}(\\mathrm{x}, \\alpha))}{\\partial \\alpha} \\mathrm{dx}\\)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Differentiate the following w.r.t. $\\text{x}$&nbsp;</strong><br><strong>(a) $\\int _{0}^{{{x}^{2}}}\\left( \\text{cos}{{t}^{2}} \\right)dt$ (b) $\\int _{1/\\text{x}}^{\\sqrt{\\text{x}}}\\text{sin}{{\\text{t}}^{2}}\\text{dt}$</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><ol><li>We have to find $I=\\frac{d}{dx}\\left( \\int _{0}^{{{x}^{2}}}\\text{cos}{{\\text{t}}^{2}}dt \\right)$</li></ol><p>This is an example of case- 1 where only limits are a function of $\\text{x}$.</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} \\therefore &amp; ~\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }I=\\left( \\text{cos}{{\\left( {{x}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}} \\right)\\times \\frac{d}{dx}\\left( {{x}^{2}} \\right)-\\text{cos}\\left( 0 \\right)\\cdot 0 \\\\ \\Rightarrow &amp; ~\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }I=2x\\text{cos}{{x}^{4}} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><ol><li>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }I=\\frac{d}{dx}\\int _{1/x}^{\\sqrt{x}}\\text{sin}{{t}^{2}}dt$</li></ol><p>This is again an example of case-1</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; ~I=\\left( \\text{sin}{{(\\sqrt{x})}^{2}} \\right)\\times \\frac{d}{dx}\\left( \\sqrt{x} \\right)-\\left( \\text{sin}{{\\left( \\frac{1}{x} \\right)}^{2}} \\right)\\times \\frac{d}{dx}\\left( \\frac{1}{x} \\right) \\\\ {} &amp; ~=\\text{sin}x\\times \\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{x}}-\\text{sin}\\left( \\frac{1}{{{x}^{2}}} \\right)\\left( -\\frac{1}{{{x}^{2}}} \\right) \\\\ {} &amp; ~=\\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{x}}\\text{sin}x+\\frac{1}{{{x}^{2}}}\\text{sin}\\left( \\frac{1}{{{x}^{2}}} \\right) \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Find the points of maxima / minima of $\\int _{0}^{{{x}^{2}}}\\frac{{{t}^{2}}-5t+4}{2+{{e}^{t}}}dt$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution. </strong>We will apply the normal rules of maxima/minima &amp; for maxima/minima we differentiate</p><p>$\\therefore $ if $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ f}\\left( \\text{x} \\right)=\\int _{0}^{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}\\frac{{{\\text{t}}^{2}}-5\\text{t}+4}{2+{{\\text{e}}^{\\text{t}}}}\\text{dt}$</p><p>then $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{f}'\\left( x \\right)=\\frac{d}{dx}\\int _{0}^{{{x}^{2}}}\\left( \\frac{{{t}^{2}}-5t+4}{2+{{e}^{t}}} \\right)dt$</p><p>again case-1 example, only limit is a function of $\\text{x}$. $\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ {f}'}\\left( \\text{x} \\right)=\\frac{{{\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}}-5\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}} \\right)+4}{2+{{\\text{e}}^{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}}}\\cdot \\frac{\\text{d}}{\\text{dx}}\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}} \\right)-0$</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} =2x\\left[ \\frac{{{\\left( {{x}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}}-5\\left( {{x}^{2}} \\right)+4}{2+{{e}^{{{x}^{2}}}}} \\right] &amp; ~ \\\\ =\\frac{2x\\left( {{x}^{2}}-4 \\right)\\left( {{x}^{2}}-1 \\right)}{2+{{e}^{{{x}^{2}}}}} &amp; ~ \\\\ =\\frac{2x\\cdot \\left( x-2 \\right)\\left( x+2 \\right)\\left( x-1 \\right)\\left( x+1 \\right)}{2+{{e}^{{{x}^{2}}}}} &amp; ~ \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>equality it to zero.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"418\" height=\"62\"></p><p>Hence the points of maxima (i.e. where sign $=-1,1$ changes from +ve to -ve) &amp; points of minima (where sign changes from -ve to + ve $)=-2,0,2$</p>",
